{"title_page": "77th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 77 Street\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = black\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| image = 77th Street - Northbound Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = Manhattan-bound platform\n| address = 77th Street &amp; [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]]<br>Brooklyn, NY 11209<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Bay Ridge, Brooklyn|Bay Ridge]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|37|42.59|N|74|1|33.37|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth far south\n| connection = {{Bus icon}} '''[[New York City Transit buses|New York City Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B4}}; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 2\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1916|January|15|p=y}}<ref name=\"Station Opening\" />\n| wifi = yes\n| code = 037\n| passengers = 1,676,402<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -15.3\n| rank = 270<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| accessible = future\n| acc_note =\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=Bay Ridge Avenue | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth far south}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=86th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth far south}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}\n}}\n\n'''77th Street''' is a [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at 77th Street and [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]] in [[Bay Ridge, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times.\n\nThe 77th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905 and subsequently modified. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 77th Street started on January 24, 1913, and was completed in 1915. The station opened on January 15, 1916 as part of an extension of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line from [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]] to [[86th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|86th Street]]. The station's platforms were lengthened in 1925.\n\n== History ==\n===Construction and opening===\nThe 77th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line. The plan for the line was initially adopted on June 1, 1905, before being approved by the [[Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of New York]] on June 18, 1906 after the Rapid Transit Commission was unable to get the necessary consents of property owners along the planned route.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC) on July 1, 1907, and the PSC approved the plan for the line in October and November 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City and the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT) and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> In 1912, during the Dual System negotiations, the construction of an extension of the Fourth Avenue subway from 43rd Street to 89th Street, just south of the [[86th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|86th Street station]], was recommended. This recommendation was approved by the Board of Estimate on February 15, 1912. The PSC directed its Chief Engineer to create plans on June 14, 1912, and the contracts for the extension, Route 11B, were awarded on September 16, 1912.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nOn January 24, 1913, construction began on Route 11B2, which includes this station and extends between 61st Street and 89th Street. Construction was completed on this section in 1915.<ref name=\":12\"/> 77th Street station opened on January 15, 1916 as part of an extension of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line from 59th Street to 86th Street.<ref name=\"Station Opening\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/55570240|title=Subway Running To Eighty-Sixth Street Starts Building Boom In Bay Ridge|date=January 15, 1916|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015|newspaper=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rpglAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA252|title=Report of the Public Service Commission For The First District of the State of New York For The Year Ending December 31, 1916. Vol. II. Statistics of Transportation Companies For The Year Ending June 30, 1916|publisher=New York State Public Service Commission|page=136|date=1917|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, 77th Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|495|feet|meters}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Legislature|first=New York (State)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ugaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA100&dq=%22union+street%22+LENGTHENING&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8_PLm7tboAhXBhOAKHVx0AzwQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20LENGTHENING&f=false|title=Second Annual Report of the Transit Commission (For the Calendar Year 1922)|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> On February 16, 1925, the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{Inflation|US|633000|1925|fmt=eq}}). The BMT had been ordered by the Transit Commission to lengthen these platforms since September 1923.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url-access=subscription|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=February 26, 1926|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{Inflation|US|345021|1926|fmt=eq}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=March 18, 1926|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=April 7, 2020|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1960s ====\nIn the 1960s, the New York City Transit Authority (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16-17}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 77th Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 in preparation of the construction of platform extensions ({{Inflation|US|6585|1967|fmt=eq}}).<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379-380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[45th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|45th Street]] station and [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street station|Bay Ridge\u201395th Street]], including this station, on May 3, 1968.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHBIAQAAIAAJ&q=|title=Engineering News-record|date=1968|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=75|language=en}}</ref><!-- The information on the contract bid is likely in the 1968 Volume of Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation, but this has not been digitized.-->\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended {{Convert|85|feet|meters|abbr=}} to the north,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"northend\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Line, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=February 21, 1970|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 7, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Station layout==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 2-tracked side platform station\n|1=Bay Ridge Avenue\n|l1=Bay Ridge Av\n|2=86th Street\n|l2=86 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=R\n|deg=330\n}}\n}}\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Street Level\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=400 valign=top|Exit/Entrance\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''B1'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Mezzanine\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=400 valign=top|Fare control, station agent\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=6 valign=top|'''B2'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|<span style=background-color:#{{NYCS color|yellow}}>'''Northbound'''</span>\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=400|\u2190 {{rint|newyork|R}} toward [[Forest Hills\u201371st Avenue (IND Queens Boulevard Line)|Forest Hills\u201371st Avenue]] ([[Whitehall Street\u2013South Ferry (BMT Broadway Line)|Whitehall Street]] late nights) <small>([[Bay Ridge Avenue (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge Avenue]])</small>\n|-\n|<span style=background-color:#{{NYCS color|yellow}}>'''Southbound'''</span>\n|<span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|R}} toward [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge\u201395th Street]] <small>([[86th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|86th Street]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right</small>\n|}\n[[File:77brstair5bbtjeh.JPG|thumb|left|200px|Stairs on east side of Fourth Avenue]]\n[[File:77 Street R vc.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Northbound {{NYCS|R}} train arriving]]\n\nThis underground station has two tracks and two [[side platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|doughtery}}</ref> The R stops here at all times.<ref name=\"ttr\">{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref>\n\nWhile the 95th Street-bound platform has columns along its full length,<ref name=\"yellowcolumns\">{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=A low-angle view down the Bay Ridge-bound platform by the staircase up to the mezzanine at 77 Street.|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r25.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref> the Manhattan-bound platform is mostly columnless, with only a few columns located in the middle of the platform and at either end.\n<ref=\"northend\"/><ref>\n* {{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=Looking down the Bay Ridge-bound side platform at 77 Street, with its round original 1915 columns |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r3.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=Looking down towards the southern end of the Bay Ridge-bound platform at 77 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r27.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"stairs\">{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=Another view across to the Manhattan-bound platform at Bay Ridge with its two staircases down from the mezzanine visible. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r28.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref> The columns on the 95th Street-bound platform are curved, except for those near the staircases to the mezzanine<ref name=\"yellowcolumns\"/> and at the north end of the platform, which are typical I-beams, and are where the platform was extended in 1970.<ref name=\"northend\">{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=The High Exit Turnstile on the Bay Ridge-bound platform for the exit to 76 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r4.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref> All of the columns are painted yellow and alternate ones have \"77 Street\" signs on them.<ref name=\"yellowcolumns\"/>\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> Since that renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain orange-painted cinderblock tiles. The blue cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=A close up of a 77 Street platform sign on the orange cinderblock indentations along the platforms, this one is on the Uptown, Bay Ridge-bound platform between its two exits because the arrow beneath it points towards the exit to 76 St. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r1.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Provisions===\nThe Fourth Avenue Line south of [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]], including the Bay Ridge Avenue and 77th Street stations, was built as a two-track structure under the west side of Fourth Avenue with plans for two future tracks on the east side of the street. The station is designed to allow the northbound platform to become the Manhattan-bound express trackway if the two additional tracks were built. To facilitate the conversion, the northbound platform is mostly columnless and is wider than the southbound platform. Furthermore, there is space underneath the platform for the trackway.<ref name=\"tracks\"/><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-BMT4Av-86StExt-Feb1912\">{{cite news|title=Brooklyn Subway Extension Plan: Fourth Ave. Line to 86th St., Tunnel to Staten Island, and Eventually a Through Route to Coney Island|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/02/16/104891453.pdf|work=The New York Times|accessdate=June 28, 2015|date=February 16, 1912}}</ref>\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n===Exits===\nThe station's full-time entrance is a [[mezzanine (architecture)|mezzanine]] at the south end above the platforms and tracks. Two staircases from each platform go up to a waiting area/crossover, where a [[turnstile]] bank provides entrance/exit from the system.<ref name=\"stairs\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=One of the two staircases up from the uptown (Bay Ridge-bound) platform at 77 Street to the fully staffed exit. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r23.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=A wider view of the mezzanine within fare control at 77 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r22.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref> Outside [[fare control]], there is a token booth and two staircases going up to either northern corners of 77th Street and Fourth Avenue.<ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Bay Ridge|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B12-Bay%20Ridge_2015.pdf|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=Approaching the token booth in the small fare control area to 77 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r16.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref> The northwest staircase has its original ornate banisters and railings.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=Approaching the original, ornate 1910s platform entrance to 77 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r11.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=A close-up of some of the detailing of the ornate 1910s platform entrance to 77 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r12.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref> Inside the mezzanine, there are mosaics indicating a newsstand and two restrooms, all of which are now closed, and directing to each platform.<ref>\n* {{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=An original Terra-Cotta sign for a long-defunct News Stand with the waiting area sign and bench on the white tiled wall beneath it in the mezzanine area at 77 Street within fare control. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r17.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=A blacked over terra-cotta sign for Men above an opened gate on the mezzanine at 77 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r20.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=A Blacked over terra-cotta sign for Women, above a closed bathroom in the small mezzanine area at 77 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r18.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=A blacked over directional mosaic sign with arrow for the downtown platform on the mezzanine at 77 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r19.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=A blacked over mosaic arrow sign for Uptown (and the Bay Ridge-bound platform) on the small mezzanine at 77 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r21.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the Bay Ridge-bound platform has an exit-only at the north end, which consisted of one high entry-exit turnstile on the platform.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=The top of the No entry exit only exit from 77 Street at 76 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r10.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref> A single platform-level exit-only turnstiles leads to a double flight staircase that goes up to the northwest corner of 76th Street and Fourth Avenue.<ref name=maps/> The landing here has the station's original trim line with \"77\" tablets on it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=The staircase up to 76 Street also has original white tiling, the only area still with its trim line is visible in this view, the bottom of the landing outside of fare control from the High Exit Turnstile. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r9.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeremiah |title=A wider-view of the intact section of platform trim-line at 77 Street at the base of the staircase up from the High Exit Gate exit to 76 Street. |url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/77r7.jpg |website=subwaynut.com |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |date=June 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:378|BMT 4th Avenue|77th Street}}\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150113014240/http://www.stationreporter.net/rtrain.htm R Train]\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/index.php 77th Street Pictures]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.629857,-74.025729&spn=0.004088,0.013336&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.629378,-74.02566&panoid=HM9TvIO_xrIbP9RW9nJIZg&cbp=12,61,,0,-0.79 77th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.630068,-74.025235&spn=0.003917,0.013336&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.630109,-74.025361&panoid=Ac8VrSjy956XIlRSqDQFsQ&cbp=12,351.08,,0,4.35 76th Street exit only stairs from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6294136,-74.0255585,3a,75y,48.95h,89.25t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s-g-HD_6mq8xE%2FWG3KOZDoVuI%2FAAAAAAAAYWY%2FSMqO1-7V8aAiWAVBOhRWirOTiBMzIV8ywCLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2F-g-HD_6mq8xE%2FWG3KOZDoVuI%2FAAAAAAAAYWY%2FSMqO1-7V8aAiWAVBOhRWirOTiBMzIV8ywCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:77th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1916]]\n[[Category:Bay Ridge, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:1916 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 77 Street\n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = black\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| image = 77th Street - Northbound Platform.jpg\n| image_caption = Manhattan-bound platform\n| address = 77th Street &amp; [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]]<br>Brooklyn, NY 11209<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/assets/doh/downloads/pdf/epi/Brooklyn|title=Borough of Brooklyn, New York City|publisher=[[Government of New York City]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Bay Ridge, Brooklyn|Bay Ridge]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|37|42.59|N|74|1|33.37|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth far south\n| connection = {{Bus icon}} '''[[New York City Transit buses|New York City Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B4}}; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 2\n| structure = Underground\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1916|January|15|p=y}}<ref name=\"Station Opening\" />\n| wifi = yes\n| code = 037\n| passengers = 1,676,402<ref name=\"ridership\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -15.3\n| rank = 270<ref name=\"ridership\"/>\n| accessible = future\n| acc_note =\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=Bay Ridge Avenue | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth far south}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=86th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth far south}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}\n}}\n\n'''77th Street''' is a [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at 77th Street and [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]] in [[Bay Ridge, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times.\n\nThe 77th Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 77th Street started in 1913, and was completed in 1915. The station opened on January 15, 1916 as part of an extension of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line from [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]] to [[86th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|86th Street]]. The station's platforms were lengthened in 1925.\n\n== History ==\nOn January 24, 1913, construction began on Route 11B2, which includes this station and extends between 61st Street and 89th Street. Construction was completed on this section in 1915.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|title=New York Division ERA Bulletin May 1961|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|work=Google Docs|access-date=May 8, 2017}}</ref> 77th Street opened on January 15, 1916 as part of an extension of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line from 59th Street to 86th Street.<ref name=\"Station Opening\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/55570240|title=Subway Running To Eighty-Sixth Street Starts Building Boom In Bay Ridge|date=January 15, 1916|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate=June 29, 2015|newspaper=[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rpglAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA252|title=Documents of the Senate of the State of New York|last=Senate|first=New York (State) Legislature|date=January 1, 1917|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe platforms were originally {{Convert|435|feet|meters}} long, allowing for six-car local trains.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGh7jL3tnTAhUByyYKHZe8BXIQ6AEIKzAB#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|last=|first=|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> On February 16, 1925, the Board of Transportation directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at twelve stations along the Fourth Avenue Line, including this station, to accommodate eight-car trains at the cost of $633,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url-access=subscription|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|last=|first=|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Station layout==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 2-tracked side platform station\n|1=Bay Ridge Avenue\n|l1=Bay Ridge Av\n|2=86th Street\n|l2=86 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=R\n|deg=330\n}}\n}}\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Street Level\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=400 valign=top|Exit/Entrance\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''B1'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Mezzanine\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=400 valign=top|Fare control, station agent\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=6 valign=top|'''B2'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|<span style=background-color:#{{NYCS color|yellow}}>'''Northbound'''</span>\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=400|\u2190 {{rint|newyork|R}} toward [[Forest Hills\u201371st Avenue (IND Queens Boulevard Line)|Forest Hills\u201371st Avenue]] ([[Whitehall Street\u2013South Ferry (BMT Broadway Line)|Whitehall Street]] late nights) <small>([[Bay Ridge Avenue (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge Avenue]])</small>\n|-\n|<span style=background-color:#{{NYCS color|yellow}}>'''Southbound'''</span>\n|<span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|R}} toward [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge\u201395th Street]] <small>([[86th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|86th Street]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right</small>\n|}\n[[File:77brstair5bbtjeh.JPG|thumb|left|200px|Stairs on east side of Fourth Avenue]]\n[[File:77 Street R vc.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Northbound {{NYCS|R}} train arriving]]\nThis underground station has two [[side platform]]s and two tracks.<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook3}}</ref> Both platforms have cinder-block tiles installed during a 1970s renovation. The original trim lines were replaced with white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain orange-painted cinderblock tiles. The staircases were repaired and new platform edges were installed. The orange cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and white text pointing to the exits. The renovation also replaced [[incandescent lighting]] with [[fluorescent lighting]].\n\nBoth platforms have yellow columns that run at regular intervals along the entire length. Alternating ones have the standard black and white station name plate. The columns are round in the center and i-beams at either ends (where the platforms were extended in the 1950s to accommodate the current standard length of a [[B Division (New York City Subway)|B Division]] train of 600 feet).\n\nThe station is built on the west side of Fourth Avenue due to plans for a possible extension of the express tracks south of [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=NYTimes-BMT4Av-86StExt-Feb1912>{{cite web|title=Brooklyn Subway Extension Plan: Fourth Ave. Line to 86th St., Tunnel to Staten Island, and Eventually a Through Route to Coney Island|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/02/16/104891453.pdf|website=[[The New York Times|nytimes.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=June 28, 2015|date=February 16, 1912}}</ref> As a result of the possibility of the extension of the express tracks, there is space underneath the northbound platform for an additional trackway at this station for the Bay Ridge-bound express track. This also can be found at [[Bay Ridge Avenue (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge Avenue]].\n\n{{Clear|left}}\n\n===Exits===\nThe station's full-time entrance is a [[mezzanine (architecture)|mezzanine]] at the south end above the platforms and tracks. Two staircases from each platform go up to a waiting area/crossover, where a [[turnstile]] bank provides entrance/exit from the system. Outside [[fare control]], there is a token booth and two staircases going up to either northern corners of 77th Street and Fourth Avenue. The northwest staircase has its original ornate banisters and railings. Inside the mezzanine, there are mosaics indicating a newsstand and two restrooms, all of which are now defunct, and directing to each platform.<ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Bay Ridge|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B12-Bay%20Ridge_2015.pdf|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the Bay Ridge-bound platform has an exit-only at the north end. A single platform-level exit-only turnstiles leads to a double flight staircase that goes up to the northwest corner of 76th Street and Fourth Avenue.<ref name=maps/> The landing here has the station's original trim line with \"77\" tablets on it.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:378|BMT 4th Avenue|77th Street}}\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150113014240/http://www.stationreporter.net/rtrain.htm R Train]\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/77r/index.php 77th Street Pictures]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.629857,-74.025729&spn=0.004088,0.013336&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.629378,-74.02566&panoid=HM9TvIO_xrIbP9RW9nJIZg&cbp=12,61,,0,-0.79 77th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.630068,-74.025235&spn=0.003917,0.013336&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.630109,-74.025361&panoid=Ac8VrSjy956XIlRSqDQFsQ&cbp=12,351.08,,0,4.35 76th Street exit only stairs from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.6294136,-74.0255585,3a,75y,48.95h,89.25t/data=!3m7!1e1!3m5!1s-g-HD_6mq8xE%2FWG3KOZDoVuI%2FAAAAAAAAYWY%2FSMqO1-7V8aAiWAVBOhRWirOTiBMzIV8ywCLIB!2e4!6s%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2F-g-HD_6mq8xE%2FWG3KOZDoVuI%2FAAAAAAAAYWY%2FSMqO1-7V8aAiWAVBOhRWirOTiBMzIV8ywCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i7168!8i3584!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1 Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:77th Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1916]]\n[[Category:Bay Ridge, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:1916 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Kew Gardens 613", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript; expand fromBay Ridge Avenue station", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/77th_Street_station_(BMT_Fourth_Avenue_Line)"}
{"title_page": "United States Postmaster General", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox official post\n| post = United States Postmaster General\n| insignia = Seal of the United States Department of the Post Office.svg\n| insigniasize = 120\n| insigniacaption = Seal of the former [[United States Post Office Department|Post Office Department]]\n| image = https://m.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=4774363415191&id=1778742358&set=a.1178576162757&source=11\n| incumbent = [[Megan Brennan]]\n| incumbentsince = February 1, 2015\n| department = [[United States Postal Service]]\n| style = Madam Postmaster General\n| status = [[Chief executive]]\n| seat = [[L'Enfant Plaza|475 L'Enfant Plaza SW]], [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| appointer = [[Board of Governors of the United States Postal Service|Board of Governors]]\n| termlength = No fixed term\n| first = [[Benjamin Franklin]]\n| formation = 1775\n| deputy = Deputy Postmaster General\n| salary = $276,840<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Keefe|first=Ed|title=Salaries of top Postal Service executives revealed|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/federal-eye/post/salaries-of-top-postal-service-executives-revealed/2011/05/10/AFGaBjgG_blog.html|newspaper=Washington Post|accessdate=5 September 2011|date=May 10, 2011}}</ref>\n| website = {{url|http://about.usps.com/who/leadership/pmg-exec-leadership-team.htm|about.usps.com}}\n| body = \n}}\nThe '''postmaster general of the United States''' is the chief executive officer of the [[United States Postal Service]]. [[Megan Brennan]] is the current postmaster general, having delayed her original January 31, 2020 retirement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://about.usps.com/newsroom/national-releases/2020/0106-postmaster-general-agrees-to-delay-retirement.htm|title=Postmaster General Agrees to Delay Retirement - Newsroom - About.usps.com|website=about.usps.com|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nAppointed members of the [[Board of Governors of the United States Postal Service]] select the postmaster general and deputy postmaster general, who then join the board.\n\n== History ==\nThe office, in one form or another, is older than both the [[United States Constitution]] and the [[United States Declaration of Independence]].  [[Benjamin Franklin]] was appointed by the [[Continental Congress]] as the first postmaster general in 1775<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://about.usps.com/who-we-are/postal-history/pmg-franklin.pdf|title=Benjamin Franklin \u2014 About UPS|last=|first=|date=February 2003|website=United States Postal Service|publisher=Historian US Postal Service|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006013742/https://about.usps.com/who-we-are/postal-history/pmg-franklin.pdf|archive-date=6 October 2019|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> serving just over 15 months. Franklin had previously served as deputy postmaster for the British colonies of North America since 1753.\n\nUntil 1971, the postmaster general was the head of the [[United States Post Office Department|Post Office Department]] (or simply \"Post Office\" until the 1820s).<ref>[http://about.usps.com/publications/pub100/welcome.htm Publication 100 \u2013 The United States Postal Service: An American History 1775\u20132006]. [[United States Postal Service]], May 2007. Also available in [http://about.usps.com/publications/pub100.pdf PDF] format.</ref> During that era, the postmaster general was appointed by the [[president of the United States]], with the [[Advice and Consent Clause|advice and consent]] of the [[United States Senate]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://about.usps.com/publications/pub100/pub100_074.htm|title=Postmasters General|last=United States Postal Service|website=about.usps.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-18}}</ref> From 1829 to 1971, the postmaster general was a member of the [[President of the United States|president's]] [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]].\n\nThe Cabinet post of postmaster general was often given{{when|date=July 2017}} to a new president's campaign manager or other key political supporter, and was considered something of a [[sinecure]]. The postmaster general was in charge of the governing party's [[patronage]] and was a powerful position which held much influence within the party.\n\nIn 1971, the Post Office Department was re-organized into the [[United States Postal Service]], an independent agency of the executive branch. Therefore, the postmaster general is no longer a member of the Cabinet<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mailboxnearme.net/history-of-usps/|title=History of the United States Postal Service|website=Mailbox Near Me|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> and is no longer in the line of [[United States presidential line of succession|presidential succession]]. The postmaster general is now appointed by nine \"governors\", appointed by the president with the advice and consent of the Senate. The governors, along with the postmaster general and the deputy postmaster general, constitute the full Postal Service Board of Governors.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://about.usps.com/who-we-are/leadership/board-governors.htm|title=About the Board of Governors|last=United States Postal Service|website=about.usps.com|access-date=2018-05-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927084552/http://about.usps.com/who-we-are/leadership/board-governors.htm|archive-date=2011-09-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe postmaster general is the second-highest paid U.S. government official, based on publicly available salary information, after the president of the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 10 Highest-Paid Government Jobs|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/pf_article_112283.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305081942/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/pf_article_112283.html|archive-date=March 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |publisher=24/7WallSt.com|accessdate=5 September 2011|author=Michael B. Sauter and Jon C. Ogg}}</ref>\n\n==Postmasters general under the Continental Congress==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Date appointed\n|-\n|[[Benjamin Franklin]]\n|July 26, 1775\n|-\n|[[Richard Bache]]\n|November 7, 1776\n|-\n|[[Ebenezer Hazard]]\n|January 28, 1782\n|}\n\n[[File:SOsgood.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Samuel Osgood (1747\u20131813)]]\n\n==Postmasters general over the U.S. Post Office Department, 1789\u20131971==\n\n===As non-Cabinet department, 1789\u20131829===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! State of residence\n! Date appointed\n! [[President of the United States|President(s)]] served under\n|-\n|[[Samuel Osgood]]  Federalist\n|[[Massachusetts]]\n|September 26, 1789\n|[[George Washington|Washington]]\n|-\n|[[Timothy Pickering]] Federalist\n|[[Pennsylvania]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/D?hlaw:7:./temp/~ammem_WqlO|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202151855/http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/D?hlaw:7:./temp/~ammem_WqlO|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 February 2017|title=Wayback Machine|date=2 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n|August 12, 1791\n|Washington\n|-\n|[[Joseph Habersham]] Independent\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|February 25, 1795\n|Washington, [[John Adams|Adams]], [[Thomas Jefferson|Jefferson]]\n|-\n|[[Gideon Granger]] Democratic-Republican Party\n|[[Connecticut]]\n|November 28, 1801\n|Jefferson, [[James Madison|Madison]]\n|-\n|[[Return J. Meigs, Jr.]] Democratic-Republican Party\n|[[Ohio]]\n|March 17, 1814\n|Madison, [[James Monroe|Monroe]]\n|-\n|[[John McLean]] Democratic-Republican Party\n|[[Ohio]]\n|June 26, 1823\n|Monroe, [[John Quincy Adams|J. Q. Adams]]\n|}\n\n===As cabinet department, 1829\u20131971===\n; Parties\n{{legend2|#EEEEEE|[[Independent (politician)|No party]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#EA9978|[[Federalist Party|Federalist]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|{{Democratic-Republican Party (United States)/meta/color}}|[[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|{{Democratic Party (United States)