Brien]]\n|[[Massachusetts]]\n|November 3, 1965\n|L. Johnson\n|-\n! style=\"background: {{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}};\" |{{Color|white|61}}\n|[[W. Marvin Watson]]\n|[[Texas]]\n|April 26, 1968\n|L. Johnson\n|-\n! style=\"background: {{Republican Party (United States)/meta/color}};\" |{{color|white|62}}\n|[[Winton M. Blount]]\n|[[Alabama]]\n|January 22, 1969\n|[[Richard Nixon|Nixon]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Postmasters general over the U.S. Postal Service, 1971\u2013present==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Date appointed<ref>Since July 1, 1971, the Postmaster General has been appointed by and serves under the [[Board of Governors of the United States Postal Service]].</ref>\n!President(s) served under\n|-\n|[[Winton M. Blount]]\n|July 1, 1971\n|Nixon\n|-\n|[[E. T. Klassen]]\n|January 1, 1972\n|Nixon, [[Gerald Ford|Ford]]\n|-\n|[[Benjamin F. Bailar]]\n|February 16, 1975\n|Ford, [[Jimmy Carter|Carter]]\n|-\n|[[William F. Bolger]]\n|March 15, 1978\n|Carter, [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]]\n|-\n|[[Paul N. Carlin]]\n|January 1, 1985\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Reagan\n|-\n|[[Albert Vincent Casey]]\n|January 7, 1986\n|-\n|[[Preston Robert Tisch]]\n|August 16, 1986\n|-\n|[[Anthony M. Frank]]\n|March 1, 1988\n|Reagan, [[George H. W. Bush|H.W. Bush]]\n|-\n|[[Marvin Travis Runyon]]\n|July 6, 1992\n|H.W. Bush, [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]]\n|-\n|[[William J. Henderson]]\n|May 16, 1998\n|Clinton, [[George W. Bush|Bush]]\n|-\n|[[John E. Potter]]\n|June 1, 2001\n|Bush, [[Barack Obama|Obama]]\n|-\n|[[Patrick R. Donahoe]]\n|January 14, 2011\n|Obama\n|-\n|[[Megan Brennan]]\n|February 1, 2015\n|Obama, [[Donald Trump|Trump]]\n|}\nNote that, while the above table indicates the president under which each postmaster general served, these postmasters general were appointed by the governors of the Postal Service and not by the president.\n\n==Living former postmasters general==\n{{As of|November 2017|df=US}}, there are four living former postmasters general, the oldest being [[Anthony M. Frank]] (1988\u20131992, born 1931). The most recent postmaster general to die was [[Paul N. Carlin]] (1985-86), on April 25, 2018. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name!!Term of office!!Date of birth\n|-\n|[[Anthony M. Frank]]\n|1988\u20131992\n|{{birth date and age|mf=yes|1931|5|31}}\n|-\n|[[William J. Henderson]]\n|1998\u20132001\n|{{birth date and age|mf=yes|1947|6|16}}\n|-\n|[[John E. Potter]]\n|2001\u20132010\n|{{birth year and age|1956}}\n|-\n|[[Patrick R. Donahoe]]\n|2011\u20132015\n|c. {{birth year and age|1955}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Postmaster General]]\n* [[John Henninger Reagan]], the only postmaster general of the [[Confederate States of America]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141003113127/http://about.usps.com/who-we-are/leadership/officers/pmg-ceo.htm Official site]\n*[https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov/listofholdingshtml/finding_aids_s.html Papers of Arthur E. Summerfield, Postmaster General, 1953\u20131961, Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library]\n{{United States Postal Service}}\n{{USPostGen}}\n{{US Cabinet leaders}}\n{{Benjamin Franklin}}\n{{USAConfGov}}\n\n[[Category:Former United States Executive Cabinet positions|Postmaster General]]\n[[Category:United States Postal Service|Postmaster General]]\n[[Category:United States Postmasters General| ]]\n[[Category:1775 establishments in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox official post\n| post = United States Postmaster General\n| insignia = Seal of the United States Department of the Post Office.svg\n| insigniasize = 120\n| insigniacaption = Seal of the former [[United States Post Office Department|Post Office Department]]\n| image = https://m.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=4774363415191&id=1778742358&set=a.1178576162757&source=11\n| incumbent = [[Megan Brennan]]\n| incumbentsince = February 1, 2015\n| department = [[United States Postal Service]]\n| style = Madam Postmaster General\n| status = [[Chief executive]]\n| seat = [[L'Enfant Plaza|475 L'Enfant Plaza SW]], [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| appointer = [[Board of Governors of the United States Postal Service|Board of Governors]]\n| termlength = No fixed term\n| first = [[Benjamin Franklin]]\n| formation = 1775\n| deputy = Deputy Postmaster General\n| salary = $276,840<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Keefe|first=Ed|title=Salaries of top Postal Service executives revealed|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/federal-eye/post/salaries-of-top-postal-service-executives-revealed/2011/05/10/AFGaBjgG_blog.html|newspaper=Washington Post|accessdate=5 September 2011|date=May 10, 2011}}</ref>\n| website = {{url|http://about.usps.com/who/leadership/pmg-exec-leadership-team.htm|about.usps.com}}\n| body = \n}}\nThe '''postmaster general of the United States''' is the chief executive officer of the [[United States Postal Service]]. [[Megan Brennan]] is the current postmaster general, having delayed her original January 31, 2020 retirement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://about.usps.com/newsroom/national-releases/2020/0106-postmaster-general-agrees-to-delay-retirement.htm|title=Postmaster General Agrees to Delay Retirement - Newsroom - About.usps.com|website=about.usps.com|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\nAppointed members of the [[Board of Governors of the United States Postal Service]] select the postmaster general and deputy postmaster general, who then join the board.\n\n== History ==\nThe office, in one form or another, is older than both the [[United States Constitution]] and the [[United States Declaration of Independence]].  [[Benjamin Franklin]] was appointed by the [[Continental Congress]] as the first postmaster general in 1775<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://about.usps.com/who-we-are/postal-history/pmg-franklin.pdf|title=Benjamin Franklin \u2014 About UPS|last=|first=|date=February 2003|website=United States Postal Service|publisher=Historian US Postal Service|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006013742/https://about.usps.com/who-we-are/postal-history/pmg-franklin.pdf|archive-date=6 October 2019|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> serving just over 15 months. Franklin had previously served as deputy postmaster for the British colonies of North America since 1753.\n\nUntil 1971, the postmaster general was the head of the [[United States Post Office Department|Post Office Department]] (or simply \"Post Office\" until the 1820s).<ref>[http://about.usps.com/publications/pub100/welcome.htm Publication 100 \u2013 The United States Postal Service: An American History 1775\u20132006]. [[United States Postal Service]], May 2007. Also available in [http://about.usps.com/publications/pub100.pdf PDF] format.</ref> During that era, the postmaster general was appointed by the [[president of the United States]], with the [[Advice and Consent Clause|advice and consent]] of the [[United States Senate]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://about.usps.com/publications/pub100/pub100_074.htm|title=Postmasters General|last=United States Postal Service|website=about.usps.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-18}}</ref> From 1829 to 1971, the postmaster general was a member of the [[President of the United States|president's]] [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]].\n\nThe Cabinet post of postmaster general was often given{{when|date=July 2017}} to a new president's campaign manager or other key political supporter, and was considered something of a [[sinecure]]. The postmaster general was in charge of the governing party's [[patronage]] and was a powerful position which held much influence within the party.\n\nIn 1971, the Post Office Department was re-organized into the [[United States Postal Service]], an independent agency of the executive branch. Therefore, the postmaster general is no longer a member of the Cabinet<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mailboxnearme.net/history-of-usps/|title=History of the United States Postal Service|website=Mailbox Near Me|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> and is no longer in the line of [[United States presidential line of succession|presidential succession]]. The postmaster general is now appointed by nine \"governors\", appointed by the president with the advice and consent of the Senate. The governors, along with the postmaster general and the deputy postmaster general, constitute the full Postal Service Board of Governors.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://about.usps.com/who-we-are/leadership/board-governors.htm|title=About the Board of Governors|last=United States Postal Service|website=about.usps.com|access-date=2018-05-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927084552/http://about.usps.com/who-we-are/leadership/board-governors.htm|archive-date=2011-09-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe postmaster general is the second-highest paid U.S. government official, based on publicly available salary information, after the president of the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 10 Highest-Paid Government Jobs|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/pf_article_112283.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305081942/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/pf_article_112283.html|archive-date=March 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |publisher=24/7WallSt.com|accessdate=5 September 2011|author=Michael B. Sauter and Jon C. Ogg}}</ref>\n\n==Postmasters general under the Continental Congress==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Date appointed\n|-\n|[[Benjamin Franklin]]\n|July 26, 1775\n|-\n|[[Richard Bache]]\n|November 7, 1776\n|-\n|[[Ebenezer Hazard]]\n|January 28, 1782\n|}\n\n[[File:SOsgood.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Samuel Osgood (1747\u20131813)]]\n\n==Postmasters general over the U.S. Post Office Department, 1789\u20131971==\n\n===As non-Cabinet department, 1789\u20131829===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! State of residence\n! Date appointed\n! [[President of the United States|President(s)]] served under\n|-\n|[[Samuel Osgood]]  Federalist\n|[[Massachusetts]]\n|September 26, 1789\n|[[George Washington|Washington]]\n|-\n