 the United States Postal Service]].</ref>\n!President(s) served under\n|-\n|[[Winton M. Blount]]\n|July 1, 1971\n|Nixon\n|-\n|[[E. T. Klassen]]\n|January 1, 1972\n|Nixon, [[Gerald Ford|Ford]]\n|-\n|[[Benjamin F. Bailar]]\n|February 16, 1975\n|Ford, [[Jimmy Carter|Carter]]\n|-\n|[[William F. Bolger]]\n|March 15, 1978\n|Carter, [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]]\n|-\n|[[Paul N. Carlin]]\n|January 1, 1985\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Reagan\n|-\n|[[Albert Vincent Casey]]\n|January 7, 1986\n|-\n|[[Preston Robert Tisch]]\n|August 16, 1986\n|-\n|[[Anthony M. Frank]]\n|March 1, 1988\n|Reagan, [[George H. W. Bush|H.W. Bush]]\n|-\n|[[Marvin Travis Runyon]]\n|July 6, 1992\n|H.W. Bush, [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]]\n|-\n|[[William J. Henderson]]\n|May 16, 1998\n|Clinton, [[George W. Bush|Bush]]\n|-\n|[[John E. Potter]]\n|June 1, 2001\n|Bush, [[Barack Obama|Obama]]\n|-\n|[[Patrick R. Donahoe]]\n|January 14, 2011\n|Obama\n|-\n|[[Megan Brennan]]\n|February 1, 2015\n|Obama, [[Donald Trump|Trump]]\n|}\nNote that, while the above table indicates the president under which each postmaster general served, these postmasters general were appointed by the governors of the Postal Service and not by the president.\n\n\n==Living former postmasters general==\n{{As of|November 2017|df=US}}, there are four living former postmasters general, the oldest being [[Anthony M. Frank]] (1988\u20131992, born 1931). The most recent postmaster general to die was [[Paul N. Carlin]] (1985-86), on April 25, 2018. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name!!Term of office!!Date of birth\n|-\n|[[Anthony M. Frank]]\n|1988\u20131992\n|{{birth date and age|mf=yes|1931|5|31}}\n|-\n|[[William J. Henderson]]\n|1998\u20132001\n|{{birth date and age|mf=yes|1947|6|16}}\n|-\n|[[John E. Potter]]\n|2001\u20132010\n|{{birth year and age|1956}}\n|-\n|[[Patrick R. Donahoe]]\n|2011\u20132015\n|c. {{birth year and age|1955}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Postmaster General]]\n* [[John Henninger Reagan]], the only postmaster general of the [[Confederate States of 